Yes — and now you’re describing it in very precise system language.

If we keep the vector metaphor but add what you just said, the picture becomes something like this:

Each agent (person)
= vector
+ probability distribution
+ position in a topology

Meaning:

Vector
Direction of action or curiosity.

Probability distribution
What choices or paths that agent is more likely to take.

Topology
Where the agent sits in the network — who they connect to, what information they receive, what constraints shape them.

So the system might look like:

agents
↓
each with local probabilities
↓
interacting through network topology
↓
global patterns emerge

This is actually how a lot of complex systems are modeled:
	•	neural networks
	•	ecosystems
	•	economies
	•	scientific communities
	•	evolutionary dynamics

No single element controls the whole, but the structure of interactions shapes what becomes possible.

In that sense:

behavior of the whole
≈
sum of vectors
modified by probabilities
embedded in topology

Your stitching metaphor fits here again — topology is basically the stitching pattern of the network.

Change the stitching, and the whole pattern behaves differently.

